<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>What is an e-payment system? How do online credit card transactions work?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Electronic payment system (EPS)</strong> is a way of paying for goods and services electronically instead of using direct cash or physical cheque. EPS simply means online transaction of values. Online Credit Card Transaction, Online Stored Value Payment System, Digital and Mobile Wallet, E-Checks, Virtual Currency etc. are some of the E-payment systems. New types of purchasing relationships, such as between individuals online and new technologies such as the development of the mobile platform, have created both a need and an opportunity for the development of new payment systems.</p>
<p><strong>Online credit card transactions</strong> are processed in much the same way that on-the-spot purchases with the major credit cards, but there are some notable differences. There being no inspection of documents, and the actual goods being purchased never even see the credit card, new types of purchases are also called Cardholder Not Present (CNP) transactions.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-50504" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/online-credit-card-.drawio.png?resize=419%2C251&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="419" height="251"></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>fig: Online credit card transactions</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>There are five parties involved, as are credit card purchases. Consumers, Merchants, Clearinghouse, Issuing Bank and Consumer’s bank.</li>
<li>There are credit card and Consumer’s bank, a messaging bank, Clearinghouse and processes begin with a purchase.</li>
<li>Consumers make a purchase online with the system to the merchant wanting to process.</li>
<li>As he enters the merchant’s tunnel, the credit card information is sent to the issuing bank through the internet.</li>
<li>Once the consumer submits, the credit card is validated. Then the merchant’s software sends to the clearinghouse by the nearest node. The issuing bank is to verify the received request.</li>
<li>The issuing bank credits the merchant’s account once validated, the issuing bank credits the merchant’s account (a money statement) account is consolidated to the consumer in the consumer statement.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the basic elements to be considered while developing an e-commerce website?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A platform that enables companies to offer goods or services to customers directly online is known as an e-commerce website. These websites offer a convenient purchasing experience, handle inventories, and streamline transactions. Basic elements to be considered while developing an e-commerce website:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Databases</strong>:<br />
Databases are essential to the creation of e-commerce websites because they store, manage, and retrieve information about goods, clients, orders, and transactions. An outline of the types, structures, and best practices of databases used in e-commerce development is provided here.</li>
<li><strong> Application Programs</strong>:<br />
When developing an e-commerce website, various application programs and software components are essential for creating a functional, user-friendly, and secure online shopping experience. These applications can be categorized into several key areas, including front-end development, back-end development, payment processing, inventory management etc.</li>
<li><strong> Integration with ERP Systems</strong>:<br />
E-commerce websites and Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) systems must be integrated to streamline corporate processes, increase productivity, and offer a smooth experience for internal teams and customers. ERP integration in e-commerce website development is a complex but essential process that requires careful planning, technical expertise, and a strategic approach.</li>
<li><strong>Integration with Payment Gateways</strong>:<br />
A crucial step in the construction of an e-commerce website is integrating payment gateways, which allow companies to safely handle online transactions. In addition to improving customer satisfaction and fostering trust, a well executed payment gateway integration guarantees adherence to security regulations.</li>
<li><strong> CMS (Customer Management System)</strong>:<br />
In e-commerce, a customer management system (CMS) is a software program that helps companies manage customer connections, data, and interactions across the course of the customer lifecycle. In order to efficiently manage customer relationships, improve customer experiences, and increase revenues, e-commerce development requires a Customer Management System. Businesses may develop a more individualized and effective purchasing experience that encourages client loyalty and pleasure by utilizing a CMS&#8217;s capabilities and connecting them with e-commerce platforms.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>How cryptography and hash functions are used in e-commerce to ensure security.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Cryptography is essential in order to protect sensitive data&#8217;s secrecy, integrity, and validity during e-commerce transactions.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Confidentiality</strong>: Sensitive information is shielded from unwanted access during transmission by encryption methods such as symmetric key cryptography (AES) and asymmetric key cryptography (RSA, ECC), which convert it into unintelligible ciphertext.</li>
<li><strong>Integrity</strong>: Data integrity is confirmed by hash algorithms such as SHA-256, which produce distinct &#8220;fingerprints&#8221; (hash values) for each piece of data. Any change made to the data will produce a new hash value, making manipulation instantly apparent.</li>
<li><strong>Non-repudiation</strong>: By combining hash functions and asymmetric cryptography, digital signatures enable parties to verify the legitimacy and provenance of a communication or document, avoiding rejection of acts committed.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Hash Functions in E-Commerce</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Storage of Passwords</strong>: In the event of a data breach, hiding plain-text passwords from prying eyes is prevented by hashing them before keeping them.</li>
<li><strong>Transaction validation</strong>: It is the process of hashing transactions to assure data integrity and that the transaction details have not been altered.</li>
</ul>
<p>In conclusion, safe e-commerce activities depend on cryptography and hash functions. They provide confidence and dependability in online transactions, preserve sensitive data, and protect user privacy.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>What is adware? How is the SSL protocol used in e-commerce?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>&#8220;Advertising-supported software,&#8221; or &#8220;adware,&#8221; is a kind of software that downloads or shows adverts on a computer or mobile device automatically. It can be installed without the user&#8217;s express permission and is frequently included with free applications. It is designed to throw advertisements on our web browsers. Some security professionals view it as the PUP (potentially unwanted program).</p>
<p>Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) was created to enable safe communication across a computer network; it has now been substantially superseded by Transport Layer Security (TLS). SSL/TLS is essential in the context of e-commerce for a number of reasons:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Data Encryption</strong>: The information sent between a user&#8217;s browser and the e-commerce server is encrypted using SSL/TLS. This guarantees that bad actors cannot intercept sensitive data while it is being sent, including credit card numbers, personal information, and login credentials.</li>
<li><strong>Authentication</strong>: SSL/TLS offers a way to confirm that the people communicating are who they say they are. This makes it easier to verify that clients are engaging with trustworthy e-commerce websites rather than phony ones.</li>
<li><strong>Data Integrity</strong>: SSL/TLS guarantees that no changes were made to the data being delivered or received during transmission. Maintaining the precision and dependability of transactions depends on this.</li>
<li><strong>Trust indications</strong>: SSL/TLS-enabled websites frequently have trust indications, including &#8220;https://&#8221; in the URL or a padlock icon in the browser&#8217;s address bar. Customers&#8217; trust and confidence in the site&#8217;s security are increased by these signs.</li>
</ul>
<p>In conclusion, SSL/TLS is crucial for safeguarding e-commerce transactions online, shielding the company and its clients from possible security risks.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>How social marketing, mobile marketing and local marketing are used in e-commerce to promote business.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Social marketing</strong> is a calculated strategy that use marketing concepts and methods to change people&#8217;s behavior for the betterment of society. By encouraging people and groups to adopt desirable habits, social marketing seeks to achieve positive social change, in contrast to traditional marketing, which largely focuses on pushing goods or services for profit.</p>
<p>Social marketing in e-commerce promote business in following ways:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Engagement and Brand Loyalty</strong>: To produce interesting content that appeals to target audiences, social marketers use sites like Facebook, Instagram, and TikTok. This includes community-building and brand-loyalty-promoting interactive postings, tales, and live sessions.</li>
<li><strong>Influencer Partnerships</strong>: In order to reach a larger audience, brands collaborate with influencers. Influencers build trust with their audience by producing genuine content that highlights products, increasing interest and revenue.</li>
<li><strong>Social Commerce</strong>: Customers may buy things directly from social media networks without ever leaving the app. The purchasing process is streamlined by features like in-app checkout and shoppable articles.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Mobile marketing</strong> refers to the methods and approaches used to connect with and interact with customers via their mobile devices, including tablets and smartphones. E-commerce companies are using mobile marketing more and more to improve consumer experiences, increase sales, and foster brand loyalty as mobile usage keeps growing.</p>
<p>Mobile marketing in e-commerce promote business in following ways:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Personalized Advertising</strong>: Using data from user activity and preferences, mobile marketing targets consumers with tailored advertisements. Push alerts, SMS marketing, and in-app ads that promote quick action are examples of this.</li>
<li><strong>Mobile-Optimized Experiences</strong>: It&#8217;s critical to make sure websites and online shops are responsive to mobile devices. Conversion rates rise and user engagement is improved with a smooth mobile experience.</li>
<li><strong>Location-Based Marketing</strong>: In order to increase foot traffic and encourage in-store sales, location-based marketing give consumers personalized advertising when they are close to a physical store.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Local marketing</strong> in e-commerce describes methods and approaches used to draw clients to a company&#8217;s website or physical location from a particular region. This strategy is especially crucial for companies that operate physically or cater to a specific local market.</p>
<p>Local marketing in e-commerce promote business in following ways:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Local marketing draw clients from a particular region. Businesses may send promotions to prospective clients when they reach a designated region by using strategies like geofencing.</li>
<li>Creating connections with nearby communities through partnerships, sponsorships, and events may increase brand awareness and adherence.</li>
<li>Businesses that optimize their online presence for local search results are more likely to show up in local consumer searches, which increases the possibility that both online and physical stores will draw in local customers.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Describe the working mechanism of search engines.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A search engine is a software accessible through a Web site that helps people find things on the Web. Search engines contain three major parts: Spider, Index, and Search utility.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Spider</strong>:<br />
It is a program that automatically searches the Web to find Web pages that might be interesting to people. When the spider finds Web pages, it collects the URL of the page and information contained in the page. This information might include the page&#8217;s title, keywords included in the pages, and information about other pages on the Web site. The keywords are enclosed in an HTML tag set called meta tags.</li>
<li><strong>Index</strong>:<br />
The store element of a search engine is called its index or database. The spider returns information to the index. The index checks to see if information about the Web page is already stored. If it is, it compares the stored information to the new information and determines whether to update the page information. The index is designed to allow fast searches of its very large amount of stored information.</li>
<li><strong>Search Utility</strong>:<br />
Search utility takes search items and finds entries for Web pages in its index that match those search terms. The Search utility program creates a Web page that has a list of links to URLs that the search engine has found in its index that match the site visitor&#8217;s search terms. The visitor can then click the links to visit those sites.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Briefly explain the electronic transaction act of Nepal.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p class="mb-2 last:mb-0">The <strong>Electronic Transactions Act of Nepal</strong>, enacted in 2008, establishes a legal framework for electronic commerce and digital transactions in the country. Key features include:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Legal Recognition</strong>: Grants legal validity to electronic records and digital signatures, equating them with traditional documents and signatures.</li>
<li><strong>Consumer Protection</strong>: Ensures consumer rights are protected in electronic transactions, providing access to information about products and services.</li>
<li><strong>Regulatory Authority</strong>: Establishes a regulatory body to oversee compliance, issue licenses, and manage electronic transaction standards.</li>
<li><strong>Data Protection</strong>: Emphasizes the importance of protecting personal data and privacy in electronic transactions.</li>
<li><strong>Dispute Resolution</strong>: Provides mechanisms for resolving disputes related to electronic transactions, including arbitration options.</li>
<li><strong>Penalties</strong>: Outlines penalties for violations, such as unauthorized access and misuse of digital signatures.</li>
</ol>
<p class="mb-2 last:mb-0">Overall, the Act aims to promote and regulate the growth of the digital economy in Nepal, enhancing trust in electronic transactions.</p>
</div>
